What are Environments in Azure DevOps?
Better Answer

Environments in Azure DevOps represent deployment targets such as Dev, QA, Staging, PreProd, and Production. They help track deployment history, monitor deployments, and control approvals before deploying to higher environments.

Project-Based Answer

In my project, we use environments such as Dev, QA, Staging, and Production. Azure DevOps tracks which version was deployed, when it was deployed, and who deployed it. We also use approvals before deploying to higher environments like Production.

Why do we use Environments?
Deployment tracking
Deployment history
Approval workflows
Environment-specific deployments
Better release management
Short Interview Answer (30 Seconds)

Environments are deployment targets in Azure DevOps. They help track deployments, maintain deployment history, and manage approvals before deploying applications to environments such as Dev, QA, Staging, and Production.

If Lead Asks

What is the difference between Variable Groups and Environments?

Answer:

Variable Groups store reusable configuration values such as Storage Account names and Resource Group names. Environments represent deployment targets and help track deployments and approvals.

